a-size-base: My cat is addicted to these
a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on August 17, 2020
a-size-base 3: I have two cats. One of them played with these sticks for a little while but didn't seem to figure out they were chewable, even when I stuck them in his mouth. Oh well, he's a little dumb anyway.The other cat LOVES them. She needs her stick fix every day. She gets one at 6pm and the other around midnight, and she knows it - when the time comes she'll go to the kitchen counter and start meowing and begging for them. Sometimes she plays fetch with the stick, but most of the time we throw it for her, she runs after it, grabs it and starts chowing down. She even figured out how to stick one end into the high pile carpet so that she can keep it stable while she gnaws on the other end. They seem to be doing a good job of keeping my girl cat's teeth clean; we have to give dental treats and water additives for the other cat. We've been subscribed to these sticks for over a year now and she goes through about three packs a month.So your mileage may vary with these sticks. From my sample size of 2, there's a 50% chance of stick addiction and 50% chance that they'll totally flop. Even so, I have to give them 5 stars because of how much my girl loves them. If they ever discontinue these, I'm going to have a very unhappy cat on my hands.Oh, and the first few times you give these to your cat, keep a close eye on them. My cat has never choked in her 1 year plus of eating these every day, but she has taken bites that were too large and immediately vomited them up after - I guess the large chunks didn't sit well in her stomach. If you have a very small kitten, they may choke.

a-size-base: I have a cat who loves to chew but..

a-size-base 3: So my cat loves to chew on pens or anything in the shape, sp I thought these would be more appropriate for him. I gave one to the dog to show him they're the same thing but time after time he still turned away from it.I do know cats don't normally find "chew" toys necessary since cats don't typically chew in the same way dogs do. So perhaps this bone broth stick is just too hard for cats in general. But i think tbr taste is fine bc other animals in the house see it as a treat. in the end I turned to just finding some some what mildly freezed dried meat treats for his chewy-like behavior.Dogs however love the bone broth stick. I gave the rest of the bag to a toy poodle owner and her 2 dogs loved them. So 3 stars for decent dog treats that has the word cat on the bag. I don't think it's a bad treat, just not for cats.

a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on April 20, 2022
a-size-base 3: When I first bought these my cat really wasn’t that interested, but she warmed up to these. This has been a lifesaver for me because my cat has a G.I. issue and I have realize that when she starts trying to chew everything in my home office while I’m working, that it’s because her tummy is aggravating her. I now leave the sticks in my desk and when she starts chewing on my artificial plants and papers and pens, I offer her a stick and she now comes running. The downside is that she can’t hold it on her own without me holding it. However, it absolutely does the trick  and stops her from Destroying my house and eating something that she is not supposed to eat. She’s also fine with just less than one stick per day.It’s surprisingly sit well on her stomach as well and that makes me happy, because there’s not a lot of treats out there that she can have with a diet that she’s on. I don’t think of these like a cat treat, but more of a chew therapy for a cat that needs to chew on some thing. Hope this helps people in similar situations. Best advice, offer it to your cat when you see them chewing because they are more likely to try it and once they try it they may like it more. Again I would not offer this as just an occasional every day treat, as there are probably better ones out there if your cat does not have stomach issues.

a-size-base 3: I ordered these two weeks ago. They finally arrived. They were a hit with Mr. Biggles. He is a 13 week main coon/bengal tabby mix, and he still hasn't mastered how to chew on the stick but he loves the flavor and is definitely interested in them. The stick themselves ARE soft enough for a cat to break the stick down with bites and chunks. If you do own a cat that is a chewer, then you may want watch them, just so they don't choke. I'm glad that it is easy for the cat to chew but not too soft that Mr. Biggles looses interests or eats them and moves on. Considering that there are enough chew bones in a 3.37 oz package, being that they are 4" sticks each, I feel that they will last several month. Mr. Biggles is teething, but that much of a chewer. Being that these are all natural and made in the USA, this makes the product an even more handsome buy. ***Edit Review**** My. Mr. Biggles eats the stick in 4 minutes or less. He mastered this by 7 months old. They are his 2nd favorite to chew on, 1st is bison lung. He has clean teeth and no bad breath. I moved on to bully and raw hide, it lasts longer.

a-size-base: Cats LOVE these! Great for teething
a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on December 7, 2019
a-size-base 3: My cats LOVED these as soon as they smelled them! Fantastic idea for teething kittens. My kitten won't use any teething toys, but he loves these!I don't really understand how someone can complain about there being more wheat and corn than chicken in this. They are supposed to be hard to wear down. I can't see this being possible with chicken being the primary ingredient. The formulation is perfectly right for what the product actually IS. Your cat isn't going to sit there and eat the entire thing in one sitting, so I'm pretty sure a little more wheat and corn than chicken isn't going to kill them.If you don't like the idea of your cats chewing on anything that isn't pure meat, you're not going to find anything like this usable. If your cat is allergic, you already know they are because you'll have to purchase special food for them, as well. N.y cats eat natural food, where meat is the primary ingredient, and there's still some veggies and grains in there, because in general they are GOOD for them and make up part of a well balanced diet.If your cat has allergies, though, you'll be happy to know there are catnip sticks on Amazon, too, which are literally sticks that have been broken off from the plant. Problem solved.This product though doesn't deserve the bashing another reviewer here gave it. My cats love it, they love their food too for that matter (they were the ones that picked it), and they're healthy. That's all I can really ask for.

a-size-base 3: My cat isn't totally wild about them, but he does eat them. Sometimes I have to play with him a bit to get him to eat them. That is the only reason they are four stars instead of five. However, they work as advertised as dental treats. My little guy had tartar issues that led to bad breath and having two of his teeth pulled (not the fangs, thank goodness). Talked to the vet about how to improve, and she suggested chew treats. I had already tried Greenies, but my greedy cat gobbled them whole without chewing them. Definitely needed something in stick form that he would have to pull apart. Stumbled across these on Amazon and they work great. No more bad breath, and more importantly, no more dental issues. He gets a clean bill every checkup! He is actually scheduled to have his teeth cleaned once a year, but the vet recommended skipping the last time because his teeth were in such great shape. Worth the effort to get him to eat one every day!

a-size-base: Too dry? Wrap in moistened paper towel and refrigerate for 24 hours. Solution to Cats that obsessively chew on non food items!
a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on January 20, 2018
a-size-base 3: "Solution to My cat obsessively chewing on non food items like:  Power Cords, String, Yarn, Hair, Hair Ties, Rubberbands, Blind Cords, Twist Ties, Shoe Strings, Pens, Pencils, Thread, Dental Floss, etc....  He even chewed up and swallowed  a soft rubber-like small ball.  This is a condition cats get from being taken away from their mother too soon.  Keep close tabs on string like objects, Coat all power cords with "Bitter Apple Spray", and give him a N-Bone Cat Chew Treat!  Your cat doesn't like them? Try dipping it in butter.  Try holding it for him while he chews it up.  The cat chews are meant to be pliable.  Too dry?  Just wrap in a moistened paper towel and keep in the fridge for 24 hours.  They soften right up.  My cat goes on the hunt for something to chew on.  He sniffs the power cord smelling for one that is not sprayed with bitter apple.  This is when I give him a a N-bone Cat Treat and spray or respray the power cords!  It also helps to play with your cat daily!

a-size-base: Hit with our teething (potentially pica syndrome) kittens!
a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on June 15, 2021
a-size-base 3: One of my kittens seems to eat through everything (toys, random non-toy items, strings, wires, balls, etc.) and he's also teething; he may have pica. I know there are kitten toys that are made out of a rubber, but my kittens can chew through and eat that too. They are monsters. I wanted to find something that he would be able to chew, but is also safe to eat. I've tried silvervine sticks, these N-Bone chew treats, and other natural chew-friendly cat toys made of silvervine, but he absolutely loves this treat! I give it to him once a day (or when I remember) and it seems to help with his urge to eat through things. It's a hit with our kittens, but we did have to teach them that it was ok to chew. Once they started chewing it, they absolutely loved it.

a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on January 3, 2023
a-size-base 3: I thought these would be good for my two cats that like to chew on cardboard.  They both looked at them and kicked them around.  That was it.  They didn't even try to chew them so there must not have been a smell to them.  I was very disappointed that these didn't work out.

a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on May 16, 2013
a-size-base 3: My cat is a 1 year old Turkish Van who is a big chewer. He has a problem with eating things he's not supposed to and I was looking for something to help relieve his chewing on bad things. I always hated how they didn't have any good chew things for cats because I can attest that chew cats exist! Well my cat didn't want anything to do with these chews... The packaging makes it look like it's a meaty chew, but its actually a firm clear-ish gelatinous stick, I'm assuming its a juice or or artificial flavoring? I won't be buying these again, but I'm glad this is on the market because I'm sure some cats would love it, just not mine. It's well packaged and is resealable. I'd like to suggest an alternative that I found that my cat actually likes. It's Dogswell Happy Hips Salmon or Chicken Jerky. They're made for dogs but they're just dehydrated meat with no hormones or additives so it's good for cats too, and your cat may like it if it doesn't like these because it's actually meat!

a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on January 29, 2015
a-size-base 3: I can't give the sticks 5 stars because out of my pride of cats, most don't like these sticks. However, when you have 2 who like to play fetch, and gnaw on things because they're young and full of energy and like to chew on things they shouldn't, they love these. I will add though, that they do like Sentry Petrodex VS Dental Twist Treats better, but I want to make sure there's something for them to chew and give them options. The other cats besides these two, just stare at the sticks and walk away after sniffing them. Putting it into their food dish isn't even a good hint. So, your cat will either really love them or really hate them. It only takes one bag to find out.

a-size-base: Hard chewing kitten loves the flavor but too tough for him to eat

a-size-base 3: We have an 8 month old kitten who is a chewing fiend. The tender meaty stick treats might last all of 90 seconds with him. a-size-base: Not even neighborhood animals would touch it
a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on August 28, 2020
a-size-base 3: I was trying various "stick" type treats for my cat since those are his favorite; he loves chewing, and I was hoping to find some that gave him a little more to chew on and not be scarfed down. Well, these are not it, because he didn't even register that it was food. He sniffed it, and then rubbed his face on it and walked off.Ok, I certainly don't blame a product for my cat not liking it; cats can have different taste just like people. As I do with many treats my cat doesn't care for, I tried giving it to my neighbor's outdoor cat who visits daily (needless to say, for treats). She was completely uninterested. I laid it on the doormat thinking she might go for it eventually, and I had to go back to work and forgot about it. Over the next couple hours, not one but two of my neighbor's dogs came by (up to my door, where they stare intently at my cat through the screen). The NEXT DAY, after which who knows what else (including y'know, bugs and other wildlife) could have eaten the blasted thing, there it was, whole, on my door mat.I'm not positive what is in this, but whatever it is, it must be really, really unappetizing.

a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on August 28, 2016
a-size-base 3: 16 years ago, I got these for my teething kitten. She was meh about them except when I was shoving them in her mouth to save my fingers from sharp little teeth. Got them 5 years ago with the same results for my sister's kitten I was watching while she was deployed. They held more interest when fresh and soft... Once opened and out of the package, they hardened and had to be tossed in a few days.Got 2 kittens this past week, and again--in need of something to shove in their mouth when they go after my fingers. They are a hit with these babies!I feed high quality pet food and treats, and while the ingredients in this don't fit my normal standards, I want something for a few months that they can gnaw on and won't cause blockages if ingested. The majority of toys for kittens are either too soft for teething or hazardous when viciously chewed.  This is a perfect compromise--won't harm teething kittens.
